  <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)] mb-5 sm:mb-6">The Science of Dog Aging: Why Breed Size Matters</h2>

  <div class="space-y-5 sm:space-y-6 text-[0.8125rem] sm:text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">
    <p>
      For decades, dog owners relied on a simple rule: one dog year equals seven human years. While easy to remember, this formula is scientifically inaccurate and can lead to misunderstandings about your dog's true age and health needs. Modern veterinary science has revealed that dog aging is far more complex — and fascinating.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">The DNA Methylation Breakthrough</h3>
    <p>
      In 2019, researchers at the University of California, San Diego published a groundbreaking study in the journal <em>Cell Systems</em>. They discovered that DNA methylation — a biological clock that tracks aging at the molecular level — follows a predictable pattern in dogs that closely mirrors human aging. This led to the formula: <strong>Human Age = 16 × ln(Dog Age) + 31</strong>, where "ln" is the natural logarithm.
    </p>
    <p>
      This formula reveals that dogs age much faster than humans in their early years. A 1-year-old dog is equivalent to a 31-year-old human, and a 2-year-old dog is about 42 in human years. After this rapid early development, the aging rate slows down considerably.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Why Breed Size Changes Everything</h3>
    <p>
      The 16 × ln(dog age) + 31 formula provides a baseline, but it doesn't account for one crucial factor: breed size. Veterinary research consistently shows that smaller dogs live longer and age more slowly than larger breeds. A Chihuahua at age 10 is biologically much younger than a Great Dane at the same age.
    </p>
    <p>
      Scientists believe this is due to the "life history theory" — larger animals tend to grow faster, reproduce earlier, and have shorter lifespans. In dogs, this pattern is exaggerated by selective breeding. Giant breeds like Great Danes grow from puppy to full size in just 18 months — a metabolic rate that accelerates cellular aging and increases cancer risk.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Breed Size Life Expectancy Guide</h3>
    <p>
      Understanding your dog's expected lifespan helps you plan for their care at every stage:
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-3 pl-4 sm:pl-5">
      <li><strong>Small breeds</strong> (under 20 lbs): 12-16 years. Examples: Chihuahua, Pomeranian, Shih Tzu.</li>
      <li><strong>Medium breeds</strong> (20-50 lbs): 10-14 years. Examples: Beagle, Bulldog, Border Collie.</li>
      <li><strong>Large breeds</strong> (50-90 lbs): 8-12 years. Examples: Labrador, Golden Retriever, Husky.</li>
      <li><strong>Giant breeds</strong> (90+ lbs): 7-10 years. Examples: Great Dane, Saint Bernard, Mastiff.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Life Stages of Dogs by Breed Size</h3>
    <p>
      Dogs progress through six distinct life stages: Puppy, Teenager, Young Adult, Adult, Senior, and Elder. The timing of these transitions varies significantly by breed size:
    </p>
    <p>
      Small breed dogs remain puppies for about 6 months, reach adulthood around 2 years, and don't enter their senior years until age 11-12. In contrast, giant breed dogs enter adulthood as early as 5 years and are considered seniors by age 7-8. This means a 6-year-old Chihuahua is in its prime, while a 6-year-old Great Dane is nearing retirement.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Why Accurate Age Calculation Matters</h3>
    <p>
      Knowing your dog's true biological age — not just their birthday — has practical implications for their care. Senior dogs need different nutrition, more frequent veterinary checkups, and adjusted exercise routines. They're also more susceptible to age-related conditions like arthritis, dental disease, and cognitive decline.
    </p>
    <p>
      By using a breed-size adjusted calculator, you can:
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-3 pl-4 sm:pl-5">
      <li>Determine the right time to switch to senior dog food</li>
      <li>Schedule appropriate health screenings and vaccinations</li>
      <li>Recognize age-related behavioral changes</li>
      <li>Plan for end-of-life care with realistic expectations</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Tips for Extending Your Dog's Lifespan</h3>
    <p>
      While genetics play a significant role, lifestyle factors can help your dog live a longer, healthier life:
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-3 pl-4 sm:pl-5">
      <li><strong>Nutrition:</strong> Feed high-quality, age-appropriate food. Avoid overfeeding — obesity is a major health risk.</li>
      <li><strong>Exercise:</strong> Provide daily physical activity appropriate for their breed and age. Mental stimulation is equally important.</li>
      <li><strong>Veterinary Care:</strong> Schedule annual checkups, maintain vaccinations, and practice parasite prevention.</li>
      <li><strong>Dental Health:</strong> Regular teeth cleaning prevents periodontal disease, which can affect heart and kidney health.</li>
      <li><strong>Weight Management:</strong> Keep your dog at a healthy weight. Even moderate obesity can reduce lifespan by 2-3 years.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
